00:02:18.090 --> 00:02:20.280
seven or eight, when I
would go to his house.

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:22.020
He had bought these
little eight-ounce,

00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:23.424
barrel-shaped beers.

00:02:23.424 --> 00:02:24.840
And he would give
me one of those.

00:02:24.840 --> 00:02:28.800
So I've been a beer lover
since, you know, walking time.

00:02:32.256 --> 00:02:35.080
I also enjoyed
your story about--

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:39.150
I think you described it as
choking down your first IPA

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:40.850
at the local brew pub.

00:02:40.850 --> 00:02:43.980
What do you think about that
today when thinking back?

00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:45.870
JOHN HOLL: You know,
so it's twofold.

00:02:45.870 --> 00:02:48.000
And I don't want to
disparage too much.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:49.950
I still go back to
that brewery where

00:02:49.950 --> 00:02:55.000
I drank my first IPA
on draft, as it were,

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:55.860
on my 21st birthday.

00:02:55.860 --> 00:02:57.480
I walked into this
local brew pub,

00:02:57.480 --> 00:03:01.140
and I forced myself to
drink a beer because I

00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:02.490
wanted to drink better beer.

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:05.130
I wanted to be accustomed
to something that was not

00:03:05.130 --> 00:03:08.430
what everybody was drinking at
the frat parties or the college

00:03:08.430 --> 00:03:09.270
parties.

00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:10.840
And the bartender
served me this IPA

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:13.330
and laughed at me as I was
like, ugh, this is terrible.

00:03:13.330 --> 00:03:17.040
You know, he sounded like
Cleo in the beginning.

00:03:17.040 --> 00:03:19.170
But the cool thing is that
the bartender actually

00:03:19.170 --> 00:03:21.120
explained hops to me.

00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:24.840
And when we think about IPAs,
and it's the most popular craft

00:03:24.840 --> 00:03:29.380
beer style right now, it's
bitter for the most part.

00:03:29.380 --> 00:03:32.400
It's hop forward, and hops are
part of the cannabis family.

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:34.650
You can't do with hops
what you do with cannabis.

00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:36.660
Like, don't try.

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:39.570
I don't know what the policy
is here, but just don't.

00:03:39.570 --> 00:03:42.690
Hops are good for making
beer and making beer only.

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:45.490
But in those early
days, and even still,

00:03:45.490 --> 00:03:47.800
it's a bittering agent
in a lot of ways.

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:49.770
And when you say
"bitter" to people, like,

00:03:49.770 --> 00:03:52.334
oh, I don't want to try bitter.

00:03:52.334 --> 00:03:54.000
But this bartender
started talking to me

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:57.060
about pine and grapefruit
and citrus and some

00:03:57.060 --> 00:03:59.070
of these other
flavors and aromas

00:03:59.070 --> 00:04:00.990
that are derived from hops.

00:04:00.990 --> 00:04:03.540
And I think once you can
flip your brain to that

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:05.790
and start thinking about
it those ways as opposed

00:04:05.790 --> 00:04:08.100
to just the bitter
sensation, but actually

00:04:08.100 --> 00:04:10.194
what it is that we're
tasting and experiencing,

00:04:10.194 --> 00:04:11.860
it brings you around
in a whole new way.

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:15.510
So I'm really grateful that I
ordered a second pint that day

00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:18.790
and that it inadvertently set
me off to where I am right now.

00:04:18.790 --> 00:04:22.630
Which is, again, in this,
you know, cool room.

00:04:22.630 --> 00:04:25.050
KEVIN NELSON: I used to
travel quite a bit to England

00:04:25.050 --> 00:04:27.910
in my 20s, so long time ago.

00:04:27.910 --> 00:04:30.270
And remember what a revelation
it was to go to a pub

00:04:30.270 --> 00:04:34.890
there and have a cask ale,
a pulled English bitter.

00:04:34.890 --> 00:04:36.732
And these days,
the term "bitter"

00:04:36.732 --> 00:04:38.940
is kind of a misnomer compared
to what we drink today

00:04:38.940 --> 00:04:40.260
with West Coast IPAs.

00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:42.210
But it was my
introduction to the--

00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:44.710
I think you described it
as non-beer-tasting beer.

00:04:44.710 --> 00:04:45.690
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

00:04:45.690 --> 00:04:49.829
And I think beer-flavored beer
is one of these things where--

00:04:49.829 --> 00:04:51.870
and I talked about this
a little bit in the book.

00:04:51.870 --> 00:04:54.630
But we lost our food
traditions in a lot

00:04:54.630 --> 00:04:57.270
of ways in the same time that
we lost our beer traditions.

00:04:57.270 --> 00:04:59.980
And so we used to know where
all of our food came from,

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:03.060
and we used to know
where our beer came from.

00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:05.900
Before Prohibition, there was
something like 4,300 breweries

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:07.670
operating in the
country, which is crazy

00:05:07.670 --> 00:05:09.380
when you think about it.

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:11.930
And back in those times, if
you were drinking local beer

00:05:11.930 --> 00:05:14.410
in wherever city you were in,
you knew where it came from.

00:05:14.410 --> 00:05:16.910
And you knew where your meat
came from, and your vegetables,

00:05:16.910 --> 00:05:18.560
and your bread, and your
cheese, even if you made it

00:05:18.560 --> 00:05:19.700
at home kind of thing.

00:05:19.700 --> 00:05:22.280
And then we lost
our way with, like--

00:05:22.280 --> 00:05:25.460
Velveeta became--
instead of real cheese

00:05:25.460 --> 00:05:27.422
and fresh-baked bread,
it was Wonder Bread,

00:05:27.422 --> 00:05:29.630
and a plastic tray in the
microwave for five minutes,

00:05:29.630 --> 00:05:31.100
and we called it dinner.

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:32.900
And before
Prohibition, the beers

00:05:32.900 --> 00:05:35.900
were stouts and saisons and
ales of all different kinds,

00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:37.635
and spruce tip, whatever.

00:05:37.635 --> 00:05:39.260
And then, by the time
we got out of it,

00:05:39.260 --> 00:05:41.640
it was all beer-flavored
beer in the same way.

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:45.759
And so we've sort of come back
a little bit in a great way

00:05:45.759 --> 00:05:48.050
where you can eat local and
you can drink local in ways

00:05:48.050 --> 00:05:49.370
like you haven't before.

00:05:49.370 --> 00:05:50.930
KEVIN NELSON: Yeah, interesting.

00:05:50.930 --> 00:05:53.390
Beer, of course, has
an ancient history.

00:05:53.390 --> 00:05:55.220
And there's even
some scholarship now

00:05:55.220 --> 00:05:57.890
that suggests that beer is the
actual root of civilization

00:05:57.890 --> 00:06:00.260
as opposed to bread,
which we normally hear.

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:00.896
I can't think of anything
better than having

00:06:00.896 --> 00:06:01.420
people sitting in one spot--

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:03.420
JOHN HOLL: I like the
laughter that's happening.

00:06:03.420 --> 00:06:05.600
Like, people are like, yeah,
those are my ancestors.

00:06:05.600 --> 00:06:06.575
That's cool, yeah.

00:06:06.575 --> 00:06:08.450
KEVIN NELSON: And then,
of course, for years,

00:06:08.450 --> 00:06:11.967
drinking beer was safer
than drinking water.

00:06:11.967 --> 00:06:12.800
JOHN HOLL: Oh, yeah.

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:16.104
KEVIN NELSON: So maybe give
a little history on that end

00:06:16.104 --> 00:06:18.770
and also the role beer played in
the founding the United States.

00:06:18.770 --> 00:06:22.310
JOHN HOLL: Yeah, so
there's a lot of evidence

00:06:22.310 --> 00:06:26.240
to suggest that the nomadic
tribes early on would find

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:28.910
sweet grass that they would
then steep in warm water

00:06:28.910 --> 00:06:30.530
and it would become beer.

00:06:30.530 --> 00:06:34.480
Or even not steep in warm water,
just, like, naturally ferment.

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:37.880
They'd put grass in water,
and the sugars would naturally

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:40.550
ferment from the
yeast in the air,

00:06:40.550 --> 00:06:43.490
and that they would happily
get drunk off of it.

00:06:43.490 --> 00:06:45.570
And when they found places
that they were like,

00:06:45.570 --> 00:06:46.670
oh, we like this.

00:06:46.670 --> 00:06:49.760
Let's stay here,
because it's good to us,

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:53.480
and the goddess Ninkasi,
who is the goddess of beer,

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:54.810
is good to us in this place.

00:06:54.810 --> 00:06:55.580
And so a place--

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:57.134
people would stay there.

00:06:57.134 --> 00:06:58.550
But when you look
back, especially

00:06:58.550 --> 00:07:00.440
to the United States,
this is a country

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:02.030
that was founded on beer.

00:07:02.030 --> 00:07:04.490
Captain Bradford's diaries
from the "Mayflower"

00:07:04.490 --> 00:07:08.000
said, "Our victuals were running
low, especially our beer."

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.550
And so beer was potable
water on the ships.

00:07:10.550 --> 00:07:14.400
And the original plan was
to go down to Virginia.

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:16.594
But they stopped off in
Massachusetts instead

00:07:16.594 --> 00:07:18.260
and got down to the
business of brewing,

00:07:18.260 --> 00:07:23.120
because the beer on board, this
3.2 near-beer Porter, whatever,

00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:25.880
that was their food,
their sustenance they

00:07:25.880 --> 00:07:26.961
were almost out of.

00:07:26.961 --> 00:07:28.460
And then, from that
point on-- and I

00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:30.501
talked about this in the
book a little bit more--

00:07:30.501 --> 00:07:32.780
of during the
Revolution, you know,

00:07:32.780 --> 00:07:34.610
the Founding Fathers
were drinking ales,

00:07:34.610 --> 00:07:36.440
were drinking ciders.

00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:38.630
We hear a lot about how
George Washington and Thomas

00:07:38.630 --> 00:07:40.490
Jefferson were homebrewers.

00:07:40.490 --> 00:07:43.529
A lot of that's nonsense.

00:07:43.529 --> 00:07:45.320
They weren't like
sitting around the garage

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:48.230
with their sleeves rolled
up and fife music playing

00:07:48.230 --> 00:07:50.570
in the background as they're
mashing in their homebrew

00:07:50.570 --> 00:07:51.220
recipes.

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:53.210
No, it was done by the
women of the household

00:07:53.210 --> 00:07:56.820
or the slaves of the
house at the time.

00:07:56.820 --> 00:07:58.634
But they played a role in it.

00:07:58.634 --> 00:08:00.800
And then suddenly we became
a country of immigrants.

00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:03.426
And if you were a
barber or a baker

00:08:03.426 --> 00:08:05.300
or a tailor in the Old
World, you'd come over

00:08:05.300 --> 00:08:06.572
and you'd apply that here.

00:08:06.572 --> 00:08:08.780
And we were really lucky to
have a lot of brewers who

00:08:08.780 --> 00:08:10.520
came over as well and set up.

00:08:10.520 --> 00:08:14.630
And so yeah, we've had a really
long, complicated relationship

00:08:14.630 --> 00:08:18.270
with beer in this country
for a really long time.

00:08:18.270 --> 00:08:20.000
And it continues to today.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:21.350
KEVIN NELSON: Very interesting.

00:08:21.350 --> 00:08:23.864
So beer is made traditionally
with four ingredients.

00:08:23.864 --> 00:08:24.530
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

00:08:24.530 --> 00:08:27.200
KEVIN NELSON: Malted barley,
hops, water, and yeast.

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:29.090
And yeast was only
discovered a little later.

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:30.350
It kind of happened by
accident for a long time.

00:08:30.350 --> 00:08:30.450
JOHN HOLL: Right.

00:08:30.450 --> 00:08:31.310
We thought it was magic.

00:08:31.310 --> 00:08:32.900
We thought it was a
gift from the gods.

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:34.858
KEVIN NELSON: People
would use the magic stick,

00:08:34.858 --> 00:08:35.611
and they would--

00:08:35.611 --> 00:08:37.610
stirring the juice, and
it would turn into beer.

00:08:37.610 --> 00:08:38.780
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:40.250
KEVIN NELSON: And the word
"malt" is kind of funny.

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:42.083
The only other place
we hear the word "malt"

00:08:42.083 --> 00:08:44.680
is with malted milk
balls or malted milk.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:45.650
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

00:08:45.650 --> 00:08:48.140
KEVIN NELSON: What is malt,
and how did those ingredients

00:08:48.140 --> 00:08:50.207
come together to make beer?

00:08:50.207 --> 00:08:51.290
JOHN HOLL: Well, malt is--

00:08:51.290 --> 00:08:52.140
it's a grain.

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:54.140
And so you can use all
different kinds of grain.

00:08:54.140 --> 00:08:58.310
You can use rye or
sorghum or rice or corn.

00:08:58.310 --> 00:09:01.400
And a lot of brewers do
in their beer as well.

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:05.360
So it is basically a means
to get sugar into water.

00:09:05.360 --> 00:09:09.140
You boil the grain
to get it into water,

00:09:09.140 --> 00:09:12.230
and then the yeast is added--

00:09:12.230 --> 00:09:14.660
the hops are added for
flavor and for bittering.

00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:17.350
And then yeast comes
into the play afterwards

00:09:17.350 --> 00:09:20.270
and eats the sugars and creates
alcohol and carbonation,

00:09:20.270 --> 00:09:21.080
as it were.

00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:23.570
But I think, arguably, the
most important ingredient

00:09:23.570 --> 00:09:25.910
to talk about is water.

00:09:25.910 --> 00:09:29.120
And without it, we
wouldn't have beer.

00:09:29.120 --> 00:09:30.620
Without it, we
wouldn't have life.

00:09:30.620 --> 00:09:34.560
Without it, we wouldn't have our
general existence, as it were.

00:09:34.560 --> 00:09:38.570
And it's fascinating to me that
homebrewers and beer drinkers,

00:09:38.570 --> 00:09:41.400
they love talking about
hops first and foremost.

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:45.050
It's the flavors, the
aromas, the bitterness.

00:09:45.050 --> 00:09:48.772
It's a very sexy,
exciting ingredient.

00:09:48.772 --> 00:09:50.730
Water is just-- we sort
of take it for granted.

00:09:50.730 --> 00:09:52.344
We turn the tap,
and there it is.

00:09:52.344 --> 00:09:54.260
But when you think about
how much of the world

00:09:54.260 --> 00:09:56.540
doesn't have access
to fresh water,

00:09:56.540 --> 00:09:59.240
or what you see happening
in Flint, Michigan,

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:01.580
and in some other
cities as well,

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:04.340
we as beer fans
and beer drinkers,

00:10:04.340 --> 00:10:06.110
and especially as the
brewers themselves,

00:10:06.110 --> 00:10:08.810
need to be thinking about where
their water is coming from

00:10:08.810 --> 00:10:13.310
and how to protect the
resource to fight back

00:10:13.310 --> 00:10:17.150
against people who are trying
to damage our water sources.

00:10:17.150 --> 00:10:20.660
And that, to me, I think is
the most important thing that

00:10:20.660 --> 00:10:22.834
doesn't get talked about.

00:10:22.834 --> 00:10:24.500
But now that I just
bummed out the room,

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:25.760
I think we should
probably have a beer.

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:26.870
KEVIN NELSON: Yeah, so I agree.

00:10:26.870 --> 00:10:29.453
It's fun to talk about beer, but
it's a lot more fun to drink.

00:10:29.453 --> 00:10:31.280
So what are we going
to try here first?

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:33.440
JOHN HOLL: So this
is Allagash Saison.

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:34.790
I'm just going to do a--

00:10:34.790 --> 00:10:35.330
KEVIN NELSON: Thank you.

00:10:35.330 --> 00:10:36.913
JOHN HOLL: --reach
over for you there.

00:10:36.913 --> 00:10:37.960
KEVIN NELSON: Perfect.

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:40.310
And talk about
tasting beer, too.

00:10:40.310 --> 00:10:43.229
How should we approach this as
we taste our first beer today?

00:10:43.229 --> 00:10:45.020
JOHN HOLL: All right,
so right off the bat,

00:10:45.020 --> 00:10:47.330
and I'm not faulting you
guys, but this is actually

00:10:47.330 --> 00:10:48.690
really kind of cool.

00:10:48.690 --> 00:10:51.200
So on this glass, you're
going to see carbonation

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:52.280
sticking to the inside.

00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:54.238
And Cleo's going to lose
her mind a little bit.

00:10:54.238 --> 00:10:57.710
But you see the carbonation
sticking to the inside walls

00:10:57.710 --> 00:10:58.764
of the glass?

00:10:58.764 --> 00:11:00.680
That's probably because
this is a fresh glass,

00:11:00.680 --> 00:11:03.560
and it hasn't been
fully rinsed out yet.

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:06.440
But if you walk into
a place like a bar,

00:11:06.440 --> 00:11:08.695
and you see carbonation
sticking to the inside,

00:11:08.695 --> 00:11:10.070
that typically
means that there's

00:11:10.070 --> 00:11:13.130
some dust behind or
some soap residue,

00:11:13.130 --> 00:11:16.820
or something that makes
it a non-beer-clean glass.

00:11:16.820 --> 00:11:18.270
Again, we're all
fine here today.

00:11:18.270 --> 00:11:20.270
And I'm actually really
glad that that happened,

00:11:20.270 --> 00:11:23.027
because it's a pet peeve of
mine when I'm out at a bar,

00:11:23.027 --> 00:11:24.860
especially a place that
considers themselves

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:26.480
to be a beer bar.

00:11:26.480 --> 00:11:28.910
But in the same way that you'd
return a dirty fork if you

00:11:28.910 --> 00:11:32.300
got it at a restaurant, it's
just one of those things

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:33.009
to be mindful of.

00:11:33.009 --> 00:11:34.591
KEVIN NELSON: So I
want to assure you,

00:11:34.591 --> 00:11:36.890
first of all, that we
handwashed all the glasses

00:11:36.890 --> 00:11:41.664
and rinsed them, because
we knew this could come up.

00:11:41.664 --> 00:11:42.830
JOHN HOLL: It's in the book.

00:11:42.830 --> 00:11:44.430
It's one of my
things in the book.

00:11:44.430 --> 00:11:47.450
All right, so a couple of
quick ways to taste beer.

00:11:47.450 --> 00:11:50.810
First, also, when you're
doing Instagram or Twitter

00:11:50.810 --> 00:11:52.790
or whatever you guys
are doing these days.

00:11:52.790 --> 00:11:53.439
Google+--

00:11:53.439 --> 00:11:54.230
[AUDIENCE GROANING]

00:11:54.230 --> 00:11:55.890
Labels out always.

00:11:55.890 --> 00:11:58.730
Sorry, sorry.

00:11:58.730 --> 00:11:59.900
That was mean.

00:11:59.900 --> 00:12:01.340
That was so mean of me.

00:12:01.340 --> 00:12:04.130
So always labels out first
so that people can see

00:12:04.130 --> 00:12:05.930
what you're doing.

00:12:05.930 --> 00:12:07.940
Appearance is really important.

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:10.210
Think about what the
color makes you think of.

00:12:10.210 --> 00:12:12.440
Is it the color
of autumn leaves?

00:12:12.440 --> 00:12:13.670
Is it black as night?

00:12:13.670 --> 00:12:18.297
Is it the color of a
sunset or whatever?

00:12:18.297 --> 00:12:19.880
Think about what the
color of the beer

00:12:19.880 --> 00:12:22.490
makes you think of in your mind.

00:12:22.490 --> 00:12:23.870
Next thing is aroma.

00:12:23.870 --> 00:12:27.766
And you kind of get it
going to about 45 rpm.

00:12:27.766 --> 00:12:29.390
Older folks in the
room are like, cool.

00:12:29.390 --> 00:12:33.490
The hipsters are like, yeah,
and everybody else is like, huh?

00:12:33.490 --> 00:12:34.130
So you do that.

00:12:34.130 --> 00:12:36.740
And then most people will go
like this [INHALES DEEPLY]

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:37.560
to smell the beer.

00:12:37.560 --> 00:12:39.072
Don't do that.

00:12:39.072 --> 00:12:40.310
Like, don't.

00:12:40.310 --> 00:12:43.807
Not only are you going to
get the tip of your nose wet,

00:12:43.807 --> 00:12:46.140
and you don't want that, but
it's not going to help you.

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:49.130
So the thing that I kind of
like to do is like a typewriter,

00:12:49.130 --> 00:12:52.347
or like a drive by, where
you just start to inhale,

00:12:52.347 --> 00:12:53.930
and you run the glass
under your nose.

00:12:53.930 --> 00:12:55.490
So you're getting
the ambient air,

00:12:55.490 --> 00:12:56.550
and then you're
getting the beer,

00:12:56.550 --> 00:12:57.950
and then you're getting
the ambient air again.

00:12:57.950 --> 00:12:59.820
And starts to think
about flavors.

00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:01.970
And we can talk more about
that, I guess, but think

00:13:01.970 --> 00:13:03.770
about the flavors that
are coming through,

00:13:03.770 --> 00:13:05.450
the aromas that
are coming through.

00:13:05.450 --> 00:13:06.860
Does it smell spicy?

00:13:06.860 --> 00:13:08.120
Does it smell like lemon?

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:10.490
Does it smell like whatever?

00:13:10.490 --> 00:13:14.100
Then the next thing
is obviously taste.

00:13:14.100 --> 00:13:17.830
And that's the fun
part, certainly.

00:13:17.830 --> 00:13:21.070
But so much of what we perceive
as taste comes from aroma.

00:13:21.070 --> 00:13:23.560
And so think about
what you just smelled.

00:13:23.560 --> 00:13:27.719
If it was a lemon or a
cake or whatever spice

00:13:27.719 --> 00:13:28.510
that comes through.

00:13:28.510 --> 00:13:31.990
And now is it is it
much more acute now

00:13:31.990 --> 00:13:33.220
that you've tasted the beer?

00:13:33.220 --> 00:13:34.587
And it probably should be.

00:13:34.587 --> 00:13:36.670
And then the next thing
to take into consideration

00:13:36.670 --> 00:13:38.129
is mouth feel.

00:13:38.129 --> 00:13:39.670
And so you take a
sip and you hold it

00:13:39.670 --> 00:13:42.010
on your tongue for about
three seconds or so.

00:13:42.010 --> 00:13:43.600
And feel the carbonation.

00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:47.140
Is it like Scrubbing Bubbles,
or is it a little bit more flat?

00:13:47.140 --> 00:13:49.510
Does the liquid feel thick?

00:13:49.510 --> 00:13:51.384
Does it feel watery?

00:13:51.384 --> 00:13:53.800
A lot of people will say to
me, oh, I don't like Guinness.

00:13:53.800 --> 00:13:55.810
It's much too heavy.

00:13:55.810 --> 00:13:58.090
And they're just judging
the beer by its color.

00:13:58.090 --> 00:13:59.920
But if you ever take
a sip of Guinness,

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:02.180
it's very watery on the tongue.

00:14:02.180 --> 00:14:05.349
There's almost no body
to that particular beer.

00:14:05.349 --> 00:14:06.890
But some of the IPAs
that we're going

00:14:06.890 --> 00:14:09.437
to have in a minute that
are lighter in color

00:14:09.437 --> 00:14:11.020
are going to coat
your tongue and sort

00:14:11.020 --> 00:14:13.942
of this oily, slick kind of way.

00:14:13.942 --> 00:14:15.400
And then the last
thing to consider

00:14:15.400 --> 00:14:20.410
while you're tasting a beer
is really do you like it?

00:14:20.410 --> 00:14:22.600
And if so, great,
have some more.

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:26.864
And if not, if you're
like Cleopatra, it's--

00:14:26.864 --> 00:14:28.780
I'm sorry, you're just
going to be the running

00:14:28.780 --> 00:14:31.420
foil for this entire talk now.

00:14:31.420 --> 00:14:34.450
That's cool, because there's
7,000 breweries in the country

00:14:34.450 --> 00:14:36.820
right now, and they're all
making a multitude of styles.

00:14:36.820 --> 00:14:39.241
And you'll find
something that you like.

00:14:39.241 --> 00:14:41.470
Like this saison
from Allagash, which

00:14:41.470 --> 00:14:44.680
has been making great beer
in Maine for 25 years now,

00:14:44.680 --> 00:14:47.380
and is one of the top
brewers in the world.

00:14:47.380 --> 00:14:49.510
And they do
Belgian-inspired beers,

00:14:49.510 --> 00:14:51.010
and this is a
Belgian-inspired beer.

00:14:51.010 --> 00:14:53.890
And this is one of the
best examples in the US

00:14:53.890 --> 00:14:54.960
that's being made today.

00:14:54.960 --> 00:14:55.960
So that's why we got it.

00:14:55.960 --> 00:14:56.960
KEVIN NELSON: Very nice.

00:14:56.960 --> 00:14:57.462
Tasty.

00:14:57.462 --> 00:14:58.420
Everyone like that one?

00:14:58.420 --> 00:14:59.860
Who liked that one?

00:14:59.860 --> 00:15:02.230
Who didn't like that
one, besides Cleo?

00:15:02.230 --> 00:15:05.460
JOHN HOLL: All right,
but really quick,

00:15:05.460 --> 00:15:06.760
what don't you care about it?

00:15:06.760 --> 00:15:08.780
There's a guy in a
blue shirt back there.

00:15:08.780 --> 00:15:10.285
What didn't you care about it?

00:15:10.285 --> 00:15:11.910
AUDIENCE: I just
don't like the flavor.

00:15:11.910 --> 00:15:13.270
I don't know how else to put it.

00:15:13.270 --> 00:15:14.500
I mean, I like the
mouth feel, but I

00:15:14.500 --> 00:15:15.820
don't care for the flavor.

00:15:15.820 --> 00:15:18.460
KEVIN NELSON: So that
clove cinnamon flavor

00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:19.624
isn't your thing?

00:15:19.624 --> 00:15:21.040
JOHN HOLL: And
that's cool, right?

00:15:21.040 --> 00:15:22.330
I mean, and that's the thing.

00:15:22.330 --> 00:15:25.540
Like, this isn't an
attack by any means.

00:15:25.540 --> 00:15:27.610
So often in beer
geek culture today,

00:15:27.610 --> 00:15:32.159
though, people will try to
convince you why you're wrong.

00:15:32.159 --> 00:15:33.950
And I don't think that
that's a fair thing.

00:15:33.950 --> 00:15:35.410
And I think that
the smart brewers

00:15:35.410 --> 00:15:37.510
know that diversity is king.

00:15:37.510 --> 00:15:41.050
And so you can walk into
Allagash, you can get stouts.

00:15:41.050 --> 00:15:42.257
They make their table beers.

00:15:42.257 --> 00:15:43.840
They make a whole
bunch of other stuff

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:47.200
as well, because they know
that not one style of beer

00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:48.804
is going to appeal to everybody.

00:15:48.804 --> 00:15:51.220
And there's some brewers that
just make one style of beer,

00:15:51.220 --> 00:15:52.690
and I think they're
alienating themselves

00:15:52.690 --> 00:15:53.990
a little bit you know too much.

00:15:53.990 --> 00:15:57.440
So like, yeah.

00:15:57.440 --> 00:15:59.590
I think if you give
every beer a fair shake,

00:15:59.590 --> 00:16:02.173
and that's what I like to talk
about in the book a little bit.

00:16:02.173 --> 00:16:05.124
But give every beer a fair
shake, but also in the same way

00:16:05.124 --> 00:16:06.790
that if you don't
like Brussels sprouts,

00:16:06.790 --> 00:16:10.030
or you don't like goat cheese,
or you don't like anything

00:16:10.030 --> 00:16:12.490
else that we experience
in life, nobody gives you

00:16:12.490 --> 00:16:13.760
a hard time for that either.

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:15.730
So the beer fans
that try to give you

00:16:15.730 --> 00:16:18.250
a hard time for
not liking a beer,

00:16:18.250 --> 00:16:20.020
I don't think they're
doing it right.

00:16:20.020 --> 00:16:21.520
KEVIN NELSON: Go
with what you like.

00:16:21.520 --> 00:16:22.186
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

00:16:22.186 --> 00:16:24.180
KEVIN NELSON: Absolutely.

00:16:24.180 --> 00:16:27.345
So this is one style of beer.

00:16:27.345 --> 00:16:30.530
We have these four ingredients--
malt, hops, water, and yeast.

00:16:30.530 --> 00:16:31.599
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

00:16:31.599 --> 00:16:33.890
KEVIN NELSON: How do you make
different styles of beer?

00:16:33.890 --> 00:16:35.510
What goes into that?

00:16:35.510 --> 00:16:39.750
JOHN HOLL: So, so much of it
is how much you use of each.

00:16:39.750 --> 00:16:44.180
And then, again, there's
different flavor components

00:16:44.180 --> 00:16:45.650
to each of the main ingredients.

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:46.902
And so I like to--

00:16:46.902 --> 00:16:48.485
I think I might have
talked about this

00:16:48.485 --> 00:16:49.580
the last time I was here.

00:16:49.580 --> 00:16:52.190
But if you look at the
four main ingredients,

00:16:52.190 --> 00:16:54.500
and you think about
them in food terms,

00:16:54.500 --> 00:16:57.530
so water doesn't always
just tastes like water.

00:16:57.530 --> 00:17:01.370
It can have a salinity to it, or
a little bit of an iron content

00:17:01.370 --> 00:17:02.570
to it.

00:17:02.570 --> 00:17:05.490
Or it can be hard
water or soft water.

00:17:05.490 --> 00:17:08.472
But if you travel around enough,
or you grew up in a place

00:17:08.472 --> 00:17:10.430
where you got your water
from a well versus now

00:17:10.430 --> 00:17:12.109
you're getting it
from a city aquifer,

00:17:12.109 --> 00:17:15.109
you notice the different
tastes in that.

00:17:15.109 --> 00:17:18.020
And malt, depending on how
it's kilned or roasted,

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:21.829
can have every flavor from
Cheerios to Grape Nuts

00:17:21.829 --> 00:17:24.829
to chocolate and
coffee and toffee

00:17:24.829 --> 00:17:26.599
to even, like, burnt acrid.

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:29.600
You go to a good wood-fired
coal pizza place,

00:17:29.600 --> 00:17:30.860
and the pie comes out.

00:17:30.860 --> 00:17:34.560
And on the crust, you have that
little burnt bubble on the end.

00:17:34.560 --> 00:17:36.710
And everybody reaches for
it instinctively, right?

00:17:36.710 --> 00:17:38.459
And we know what it's
going to taste like.

00:17:38.459 --> 00:17:39.380
It's carbon.

00:17:39.380 --> 00:17:40.450
It's burnt.

00:17:40.450 --> 00:17:41.442
But we do it anyway.

00:17:41.442 --> 00:17:43.400
And we taste it, and it's
bitter on our tongue.

00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:45.226
Malt can taste
like that as well.

00:17:45.226 --> 00:17:47.600
There's people-- again, I use
Guinness as a great example

00:17:47.600 --> 00:17:49.266
because it's a beer
that everybody's had

00:17:49.266 --> 00:17:50.360
and everybody knows.

00:17:50.360 --> 00:17:52.830
People swear that there's
coffee and chocolate in it.

00:17:52.830 --> 00:17:54.620
There's absolutely not.

00:17:54.620 --> 00:17:57.500
Those are two
expensive ingredients.

00:17:57.500 --> 00:18:01.384
They're using malt that has
been roasted to taste like that.

00:18:01.384 --> 00:18:03.050
And then hops can
tastes like everything

00:18:03.050 --> 00:18:09.320
from grapefruit and pine
to pineapple and peach

00:18:09.320 --> 00:18:09.980
and strawberry.

00:18:09.980 --> 00:18:11.630
And there's blueberry
ones out there,

00:18:11.630 --> 00:18:15.050
and there's tangerine and
lime and lemon and mango,

00:18:15.050 --> 00:18:16.770
and everything else in between.

00:18:16.770 --> 00:18:18.900
And then yeast can
have banana and bubble

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:21.860
gum and clove and
pepper and flowers

00:18:21.860 --> 00:18:23.160
and honey and everything else.

00:18:23.160 --> 00:18:25.760
So it all just depends
on the strains,

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:28.100
and how much you're using,
and what combination

00:18:28.100 --> 00:18:29.120
you're using in them.

00:18:29.120 --> 00:18:30.760
And then you can--

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:33.470
it's game on when it comes
to brewers these days,

00:18:33.470 --> 00:18:36.360
where they're just putting--
anything goes in their beers

00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:36.860
these days.

00:18:36.860 --> 00:18:40.430
If you can eat it, brewers
have made a beer with it.

00:18:40.430 --> 00:18:42.210
And everything is on the table.

00:18:42.210 --> 00:18:44.630
Literally everything
is on the table.

00:18:44.630 --> 00:18:49.340
From money to sheep shit to--

00:18:49.340 --> 00:18:52.200
sorry, I don't know if
I can say that here.

00:18:52.200 --> 00:18:53.900
I hope you guys are cool--

00:18:53.900 --> 00:18:56.510
to all kinds of exotic fruits.

00:18:56.510 --> 00:18:59.720
I had a beer that was once
brewed with grilled beef

00:18:59.720 --> 00:19:01.160
hearts.

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:02.900
There was a beer
that Dogfish Head did

00:19:02.900 --> 00:19:06.380
that was brewed with moon dust.

00:19:06.380 --> 00:19:07.850
Everything is on the table.

00:19:07.850 --> 00:19:10.772
And it's all ridiculous, but
it can also taste really good.

00:19:10.772 --> 00:19:11.730
Sorry, this guy's got--

00:19:11.730 --> 00:19:12.410
KEVIN NELSON: I saw
we had a hand up.

00:19:12.410 --> 00:19:13.036
Can we--

00:19:13.036 --> 00:19:15.410
JOHN HOLL: See, this is the
fun part about beer tastings,

00:19:15.410 --> 00:19:15.740
right?

00:19:15.740 --> 00:19:17.020
It's always like,
let's do it at the end.

00:19:17.020 --> 00:19:19.061
And everybody's like, I've
had a couple of beers.

00:19:19.061 --> 00:19:20.570
I got things to say.

00:19:20.570 --> 00:19:22.920
AUDIENCE: I had a question
just about the saison.

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:23.690
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

00:19:23.690 --> 00:19:24.350
Aw, man.

00:19:24.350 --> 00:19:25.990
AUDIENCE: What gives it more
of the characteristic flavor?

00:19:25.990 --> 00:19:28.101
Is that the hops, or
the yeast, or the malt?

00:19:28.101 --> 00:19:30.100
JOHN HOLL: More of the
yeast than anything else.

00:19:30.100 --> 00:19:34.920
It's sort of a saison yeast
in the Belgian tradition.

00:19:34.920 --> 00:19:37.190
But also the grain
bill helps a lot.

00:19:37.190 --> 00:19:40.877
The hops are very not all that--

00:19:40.877 --> 00:19:42.710
I'm not even speaking
intelligently anymore.

00:19:42.710 --> 00:19:44.360
[CHUCKLING]

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:45.236
AUDIENCE: The chair .

00:19:45.236 --> 00:19:47.026
JOHN HOLL: I know, I'm
going to fall asleep

00:19:47.026 --> 00:19:48.380
in this comfortable chair.

00:19:48.380 --> 00:19:50.640
Yeah, the hops play a
minimal, minimal role in this.

00:19:50.640 --> 00:19:52.610
So it's usually just the
yeast strain and sort

00:19:52.610 --> 00:19:55.280
of some of the malts
that go into it.

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:57.470
KEVIN NELSON: So,
perfect transition.

00:19:57.470 --> 00:19:59.750
Hops kind of get
all the attention

00:19:59.750 --> 00:20:00.852
in the beer world today.

00:20:00.852 --> 00:20:02.060
JOHN HOLL: So much attention.

00:20:02.060 --> 00:20:02.851
KEVIN NELSON: Yeah.

00:20:02.851 --> 00:20:04.590
But like as you're
talking about now,

00:20:04.590 --> 00:20:08.282
malts and yeast really make
up that the dominant flavors.

00:20:08.282 --> 00:20:09.990
JOHN HOLL: Well, I
don't know about that.

00:20:09.990 --> 00:20:12.950
I think hops in IPAs
are the dominant flavor,

00:20:12.950 --> 00:20:14.020
and that's the idea.

00:20:14.020 --> 00:20:17.620
And these days with hazy,
juicy IPAs, where it's DDH,

00:20:17.620 --> 00:20:21.450
it's Double Dry Hop, and
brewers are putting 20,

00:20:21.450 --> 00:20:24.710
30 pounds of hops
into a barrel of beer,

00:20:24.710 --> 00:20:27.950
which is a ridiculous waste
of ingredients, in my opinion.

00:20:27.950 --> 00:20:29.540
But they're doing this anyway.

00:20:29.540 --> 00:20:33.590
No, hops are definitely, in
IPAs, the dominant flavor.

00:20:33.590 --> 00:20:35.540
But yeast is the most important.

00:20:35.540 --> 00:20:37.734
Malt gives us the alcohol.

00:20:37.734 --> 00:20:38.900
And then water is important.

00:20:38.900 --> 00:20:41.302
But hops are sexy.

00:20:41.302 --> 00:20:43.010
I mean, like, look at
this picture that's

00:20:43.010 --> 00:20:44.750
up here right now.

00:20:44.750 --> 00:20:47.810
That's a really cool-looking
piece of vegetation

00:20:47.810 --> 00:20:48.600
that's growing.

00:20:48.600 --> 00:20:50.420
And when you walk
the hop fields,

00:20:50.420 --> 00:20:54.770
and you just see binds and binds
and binds of this as you go.

00:20:54.770 --> 00:20:59.920
And it's vibrant, and it's
one of these things like where

00:20:59.920 --> 00:21:01.670
the hop rubbings, when
you go to the farms

00:21:01.670 --> 00:21:03.740
or you go to a brewery,
and you tear them open,

00:21:03.740 --> 00:21:06.020
and there's the sticky
powder on the inside of--

00:21:06.020 --> 00:21:07.190
lupulin.

00:21:07.190 --> 00:21:09.890
It's an interactive
ingredient as well.

00:21:09.890 --> 00:21:11.750
Malt, we sing about
it as kids when

00:21:11.750 --> 00:21:16.181
we're singing amber waves of
grain in the national anthem--

00:21:16.181 --> 00:21:17.180
not the national anthem.

00:21:17.180 --> 00:21:18.830
In my country 'tis--

00:21:18.830 --> 00:21:19.100
KEVIN NELSON: "America
the Beautiful."

00:21:19.100 --> 00:21:21.266
JOHN HOLL: Yeah, "America
the Beautiful," thank you.

00:21:21.266 --> 00:21:23.090
[CHUCKLES] Yeah.

00:21:23.090 --> 00:21:26.740
I wish I could blame it on the
jet lag, but I really can't.

00:21:26.740 --> 00:21:28.970
But yeah, you know,
so malt has always

00:21:28.970 --> 00:21:34.320
been a part of our
collective experience.

00:21:34.320 --> 00:21:35.380
But it's not sexy.

00:21:35.380 --> 00:21:37.660
It's not marketable
in a lot of ways.

00:21:37.660 --> 00:21:41.310
Malt goes into our cattle
feed, and our dog food,

00:21:41.310 --> 00:21:45.390
and our Cheerios in the
morning kind of thing.

00:21:45.390 --> 00:21:47.040
And it looks nice
when it's waving

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:48.810
in the breeze and everything.

00:21:48.810 --> 00:21:51.395
But hops are really
unique to beer.

00:21:51.395 --> 00:21:53.520
And so I think that that's
one of the other reasons

00:21:53.520 --> 00:21:56.670
that it's become as--

00:21:56.670 --> 00:22:00.840
I don't know, the front and
center, the mascot of beer,

00:22:00.840 --> 00:22:02.240
than anything else.

