00:22:25.652 --> 00:22:26.860
KEVIN NELSON: And then yeast.

00:22:26.860 --> 00:22:29.401
I didn't bring any of yeast in,
but if you ever get a chance,

00:22:29.401 --> 00:22:31.790
go down to White Labs
down in San Diego.

00:22:31.790 --> 00:22:33.520
They do something
really interesting.

00:22:33.520 --> 00:22:35.340
They take one wort,
which is the sugar

00:22:35.340 --> 00:22:38.490
water you start with before
you ferment it into beer,

00:22:38.490 --> 00:22:40.140
and they pitch four
different yeasts.

00:22:40.140 --> 00:22:42.030
They split it into four
different fermenters

00:22:42.030 --> 00:22:43.500
and pitch four different yeasts.

00:22:43.500 --> 00:22:45.540
So then you taste the same beer.

00:22:45.540 --> 00:22:48.810
And the only change in the
beer is from the yeast.

00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:49.815
And it is fascinating.

00:22:49.815 --> 00:22:52.200
Mind-blowing, if
you're a beer geek.

00:22:52.200 --> 00:22:53.790
You go from nice,
traditional ales

00:22:53.790 --> 00:22:57.130
to these cinnamon-y
clove Belgians

00:22:57.130 --> 00:22:58.830
with just a change in the yeast.

00:22:58.830 --> 00:23:00.950
JOHN HOLL: Yeah,
it's really cool.

00:23:00.950 --> 00:23:03.960
Yeast is all around us right
now, by the way, though.

00:23:03.960 --> 00:23:05.760
