couple hundred thousand dollars

00:40:24.380 --> 00:40:26.030
researching that.

00:40:26.030 --> 00:40:28.720
It has nucleation points
on the bottom of the glass,

00:40:28.720 --> 00:40:30.530
so all of the carbonation
is concentrated

00:40:30.530 --> 00:40:33.110
and then rises to the
top and sort of keeps

00:40:33.110 --> 00:40:34.940
this nice head of foam going.

00:40:34.940 --> 00:40:36.792
It's got a wide lip
on there as well,

00:40:36.792 --> 00:40:38.750
so you can get your lip
around it and your nose

00:40:38.750 --> 00:40:42.260
in without spill-- like, they
spent some fun time on it.

00:40:42.260 --> 00:40:44.870
The problem is, it's
really great for home.

00:40:44.870 --> 00:40:47.600
It's impractical,
even at Applebee's,

00:40:47.600 --> 00:40:51.950
because the other breweries
don't want their beer being

00:40:51.950 --> 00:40:53.870
served out of a Sam Adams
glass because that's

00:40:53.870 --> 00:40:55.580
marketing for them.

00:40:55.580 --> 00:40:57.530
The glass doesn't
necessarily stack well--

00:40:57.530 --> 00:40:59.990
maybe two or three-- before
it becomes like a Jenga

00:40:59.990 --> 00:41:01.260
game that's unwieldy.

00:41:01.260 --> 00:41:03.650
Where the shaker pint, like,
you can walk into places

00:41:03.650 --> 00:41:07.720
and it's 20, 30 deep against
the wall, as it were.

00:41:07.720 --> 00:41:10.550
So this is the cockroach
of beer glasses.

00:41:10.550 --> 00:41:13.740
It's not going to go away.

00:41:13.740 --> 00:41:15.890
But that doesn't
mean that at home you

00:41:15.890 --> 00:41:17.960
can't have great beer glasses.

00:41:17.960 --> 00:41:20.770
There's a guy in
Knoxville, Tennessee.

00:41:20.770 --> 00:41:24.110
The Pretentious Beer Glass
Company, he calls himself.

00:41:24.110 --> 00:41:25.390
And it's all tongue-in-cheek.

00:41:25.390 --> 00:41:28.910
But he has an MFA
in glass blowing.

00:41:28.910 --> 00:41:31.160
And he makes beer glasses.

00:41:31.160 --> 00:41:36.740
And it's what I use at home
when I'm feeling extra fancy.

00:41:36.740 --> 00:41:37.500
And I love it.

00:41:37.500 --> 00:41:39.125
But for the most
part, I just drink out

00:41:39.125 --> 00:41:42.290
of a tulip glass at home
just because I like the stem.

00:41:42.290 --> 00:41:43.380
I like the aroma.

00:41:43.380 --> 00:41:46.290
I like how it feels in my hand.

00:41:46.290 --> 00:41:47.109
It's kind of fun.

00:41:47.109 --> 00:41:47.900
KEVIN NELSON: Nice.

00:41:47.900 --> 00:41:48.802
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

00:41:48.802 --> 00:41:50.760
KEVIN NELSON: You talked
about bottles already,

00:41:50.760 --> 00:41:53.570
but I wanted to read a quote
from a friend of yours, Nate

00:41:53.570 --> 00:41:55.400
Schweber, you have in the book.

00:41:55.400 --> 00:41:56.090
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

00:41:56.090 --> 00:41:59.090
KEVIN NELSON: This is a
poetry about beer bottles.

00:41:59.090 --> 00:42:03.170
"As sleek as airplane wings
and smooth as polished stone,

00:42:03.170 --> 00:42:04.850
these laborers of
the beer industry

00:42:04.850 --> 00:42:07.400
sweat like construction
workers, sing

00:42:07.400 --> 00:42:10.790
like wind chimes when clinked,
and sigh like happy man

00:42:10.790 --> 00:42:13.137
when relieved of pressure."

00:42:13.137 --> 00:42:14.220
Can you say anything more?

00:42:14.220 --> 00:42:15.290
We already talked about
color and stuff, but--

00:42:15.290 --> 00:42:16.280
JOHN HOLL: No, no, I can't.

00:42:16.280 --> 00:42:18.488
And that's why I quoted Nate
in the book saying that.

00:42:18.488 --> 00:42:20.810
So Nate Schweber, who works
for the "New York Times,"

00:42:20.810 --> 00:42:23.330
who's one of my
closest friends, who

00:42:23.330 --> 00:42:24.890
wrote a great book
on fly fishing

00:42:24.890 --> 00:42:28.280
about Yellowstone, if
anybody likes to fly fish,

00:42:28.280 --> 00:42:29.930
go pick up Nate's book.

00:42:29.930 --> 00:42:31.010
Shameless plug for that.

00:42:31.010 --> 00:42:33.920
But no, it's poetic.

00:42:33.920 --> 00:42:35.450
And beer is poetic.

00:42:35.450 --> 00:42:37.130
Like, there's so
many things where

00:42:37.130 --> 00:42:39.629
I think if we just show up at
the bar at the end of the day,

00:42:39.629 --> 00:42:42.270
and we say, beer, and, you
know, we do this type of thing.

00:42:42.270 --> 00:42:45.650
But I think if we stop to
think about the artistry that

00:42:45.650 --> 00:42:48.710
goes into it, or even just
the ergonomics of a bottle,

00:42:48.710 --> 00:42:53.270
or the ergonomics of a glass,
or how a glass feels in our hand

00:42:53.270 --> 00:42:56.630
this way versus
another one, there's

00:42:56.630 --> 00:42:58.830
a lot of romance in drinking.

00:42:58.830 --> 00:43:00.950
There's a lot of
romance in beer,

00:43:00.950 --> 00:43:02.600
a lot of romance
in the ingredients

00:43:02.600 --> 00:43:04.620
and the passion that
goes in behind it.

00:43:04.620 --> 00:43:07.550
And I love that quote from Nate.

00:43:07.550 --> 00:43:09.800
I think it's some of the
most beautiful writing that's

00:43:09.800 --> 00:43:12.590
been done on beer ever.

00:43:12.590 --> 00:43:13.970
And I've read a lot on it.

00:43:13.970 --> 00:43:16.850
And I was the editor at
"All About Beer" magazine

00:43:16.850 --> 00:43:18.530
when we published those words.

00:43:18.530 --> 00:43:20.690
And as soon as I read
it, I was like, damn it,

00:43:20.690 --> 00:43:21.940
I'm putting this on the cover.

00:43:21.940 --> 00:43:23.210
It's brilliant.

00:43:23.210 --> 00:43:25.550
So yeah, I think we have
to think about it that way.

00:43:25.550 --> 00:43:26.110
KEVIN NELSON: Very nice.

00:43:26.110 --> 00:43:26.930
JOHN HOLL: Yeah.

